1 B. Absence for 10 or more consecutive school days due to placement in an interim
2 program more than 10% of the school days in a school year due to unforeseen
3 circumstances, including, but not limited to, placement in an interim program,
4 unplanned hospitalization or serious medical condition;
5 C. Enrollment in 3 2 or more schools or educational programs in a single school year
6 during the student's secondary school education; or
7 D. The student's being an immigrant student or a migrant student.
8 "Education disruption" does not include an absence for 10 or more consecutive school days
9 as a result of a planned absence for a reason such as a family event or a medical absence
10 for a planned hospitalization or recovery or pursuant to a superintendent's determination
11 developed in accordance with section 5205, subsection 2.'
12 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
13 number to read consecutively.
14 SUMMARY
1155 This amendment, which is the majority report of the committee, makes permanent the
1166 ability for a student to be eligible for a Department of Education diploma due to a
1177 significant interruption to the student's education at any point during the student's
1188 educational history as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic. The amendment also changes
1199 the definition of "education disruption" to include any housing disruption, absence for more
2200 than 10% of school days in a school year due to unforeseen circumstances and enrollment
2211 in 2 or more schools during the student's secondary school education.
